segments.text: Going back.
All right, but no one was in that fire.
No one was injured.
No, and we felt very fortunate there.
If it hadn't happened in the daytime.
But like my girls that were in their moo-moos, they put on the worst clothes that anybody could ever...
I had to go shopping before they could go to church the next day.
And you...

then where did y'all live temporarily in the old board quarters that were just across the valley from sabisa old board house just yeah and mr peniston at the time he said you know i always thought that would be the first one to burn i said oh don't say that but we stayed there about three weeks and at that time in the board

found out about the house that had belonged to Dean Brooks who had been dean of arts and sciences and he'd been long deceased and his widow was in terrible health and the doctors had her in the hospital and told her said they weren't going to release her until she agreed to either have somebody live with her or go live with somebody and see they had no children so she had a sister in Henderson that was in the same circumstance
And so she went to live with her, and it was just most fortunate for us because we just walked in and everything was there.
And where was this located?
Oh, 115 Lee.
Ah.
Do you know where, oh, Ann Lou Jessup lives now?
Right there at Southside.
Yeah, just a half block off the George Bush Drive.
Now, you lost almost all of your furniture.
Oh, yes.
And what I didn't lose went into storage.
And Earl and I went around and put our name tag on things that were ours, because so many of the things that were brought up there for storage belonged to the university.
So we put our name on things that belonged to us.
And I had a nice piano, but it got kind of scorched a little bit because of having the grand piano downstairs that belonged to the university.
Mine was up on the stair landing.
I was in George Stewart's music company one day.
He said, by the way, I've almost got that piano refinished that I bought from the university.
I said, which one did you buy, George?
He said, bought the one that was in the fire.
I said, how'd you do that?
That was mine.
He said, well, they advertised it on the surface property sale.
He said, I got it for $76.
I said, oh, my word.
It had been $1,050 at the time I bought it.
But anyway, Earl would not get disturbed about small matters.
And I told him, I said, Earl, they sold my piano for $76, and he almost had it refinished.
Anyway, Earl said, well, tell them to give us the $76.
I think they paid him $75, and we just wrote that up to a loss.
All right, then the new house.
Loved it.
Who selected the location?

I hate to say it, but Doris Hannigan and I, we walked the campus one day, and we decided it didn't need to be right down there in the middle of where all day and all night you heard footsteps, that if we put it out there, the direction facing it, it looked like it was out in the open.
But really, Doris and I, but we didn't say anything.
The board met, and it staked it out between where Malin Sutherland is and that corner.

and they would have had to cut down a bunch of the big oak trees and it and it would look out into the look at the front door you'd look at the dormitories and at the back you look at something so I just kind of moaned and groaned about it they had a stake there but you know they left them there till the next meeting then they moved them I don't know I never did know what happened but they put it exactly where we thought it ought to go now I've heard that Mr. Rutter is the one
that identified the exact way it would face.
Somebody told me that he said, I want to be the first Aggie to see the sunrise.
I don't know.
But you know where he wanted to put that?
Where?
Back in Hensel Park, where it was hidden.
I said, Earl, you know those Aggies.
I said, they're going to want to come back to that campus and say, there's the president's house.
No, he really did.
He was serious about it.

uh and uh let's see local architect did the yes dd matthews good aggie and then gene donahoe was a decorate and bob bernath oh people would not believe and and there's some difference opinion on this but i remember earl saying it was the best bargain the state of texas had but it cost the state because it cost the state sixty thousand
So, and because, see the brick, I'm glad you asked.
The brick that house is made from was old brick that was handmade in Hearn in the early, early 1890s, and they built the science hall from it.
At the time the old house burned, they'd already decided to tear the science hall down and put another building there.
So they just reserved enough of that brick to build the house.
So that didn't cost anything.
And Bob Bernath gave all the concrete.
And Dr. Boyle, Dow Chemical, gave all the insulation.
Of course, Dee Dee and Gene Donahoe both donated their services.
R.B.
Butler built it at his cost of first rate materials.
I've always thought it is pleasant looking but not ostentatious.

But you know there was some one architecture professor in particular that took exception to it he said after all this is the 1960s not the 1860s he thought it should be a contemporary and the first plan Haskell was the most contemporary thing you've ever seen and we were over there I was at home without Earl and over there on Lee Street
And this man came and spread them out on the dining room table.
I had to stop myself to keep from gasping.
It was one story, and it looked like Memorial Funeral Home, only larger.
And the window went all the way up into the eave, you know.
And he walked in, and there was a little square in the center of the foyer.
And I said, what's that?
He said, that's where the heating and air conditioning is, in the foyer.
And on the left hand side was living room, dining room, breakfast room, kitchen, utility, garage.
And then on the right, there's a long hallway with bedrooms all the way up and down it.
So I said, well, I'll show it to Earl just the minute he comes in.
Earl had the same opinion of it as I did.
And then we were at a party
at Henry Clay's a couple of weeks later, and D.D.
Matthews was there, and he said, is anything doing on the plans of the president's house?
I said, well, they brought a set of plans by, but we don't care for them.
He said, what are you having in mind?
I said, well, I think Georgian Colonial is always pretty.
And he said, let me fool around with it and see what I can come up with.
So he drew the plan.
And he didn't charge, as I understand it, and Gene didn't either for their services.
I've always thought it was very pleasant.
Did the children like it?
Oh, yeah.
We all enjoyed it.
How did the children, what were their experiences at A&M Solid Aids schools?
Did they ever have anybody pick on them because they were the sons or daughters?
You know, I don't think, they were not really conscious of the fact their daddy did what he did.
None of my kids.
They were all, you know, just ordinary.
Good, good.

uh let's see uh do you remember any good bull aggie jokes or anything that happened in or around the president's house or office yeah i remember when he got burned in effigy in the middle of the night one night scared me half to death uh because of the admitting the girls oh where was that right there
In the old house that was on 100 Jones Street, as I remember the address, and it had this huge oak tree out in front, and they put a dummy up there and set it on fire, whatever.
But you say good bull.
You know, there's, I think, a couple of books that has that title, and I was asked to put my stamp of approval on one, but I read the first bit of it, and I thought, mm-mm, not going to do that.
I would tell you why if you didn't have that machine going.
Do you remember any things being left on the front porch?
Did anybody ever leave any?
Yeah, there's one horrible.
In the new house, I still call it the new house, some animal they left dead there.
But we just called somebody, and they came and got it.
Oh, and let's see, the dog.
Ranger.
Ranger.
Yeah.
Now, where, how old was Ranger?
Did y'all bring Ranger to College Station?
No.
We had had one in Brady.
Okay.
Earl, when Earl was on that Victory Loan train roundabout, when he got to Shreveport, I believe, Louisiana.
Everywhere the train would stop, Earl would see if he could find an English Bulldog.
And you know, I was so dumb, it didn't occur to me why he always wanted an English Bulldog.
Well, he played on Eden's first football team, and they were the Bulldogs, and they were these ugly English Bulldogs.
And then when he coached at Brady, same thing.
They were the English Bulldogs as a mascot.
That's why.
And that's the only kind of dog he'd even consider.
But he got that one when he was on this Victor Loom train tour.
And we met the train, the kids and I, Bud and Ann and I, in San Antonio, and I went ahead

We had a reservation at the St. Anthony's, got them to bed, and Earl came, rapped on the door, and I opened the door, and there he was with a soldier behind him carrying a big box, and I couldn't imagine.
He had not told me what to expect, and it was a little English bulldog puppy, five or six weeks old.
And it was on a three-hour schedule to eat.
And every three hours, that little dog would yelp.
And so I knew that as soon as I got him back to Brady, I was going to break that habit, which I did.
But he was just a little over two years old, and a dog poisoner at Brady got him.
He was the first ranger.
And they threw the poison in the yard he was in the yard.
Anyway, then the next one we had, Bud found it in Austin.
He knew that Earl liked that kind of dog.
But we had a little terrier.
It's somebody who couldn't take it to where they were moving in an apartment.
And they gave it to us.
It was a cute little old dog.
It wasn't a fine dog or anything, but we all liked it.
And Earl had been out of town and had Bud driving him
And they came in late at night, and that little old dog always just slept beside the driveway.
And as they came in with the lights, it jumped up, ran in front of the car, and they killed it.
Bud was driving, and he was just upset it could be.
So he went to Austin, and he found this bulldog that everybody liked.
The kids, you know, it was such a character.
And I guess it was probably about seven years old, maybe.
And...
would eat in the mess hall.
Kids would feed him.
And he, I think he died from being overfed.
He had a kidney disease.
He died during SCONA one year.
And all the kids, oh, they were all upset and had the biggest dog funeral I bet there ever was.
The whole Corps was there, which meant everybody, you know.
And all we had to do was to pick the spot where we wanted him buried.
They took over from there.
So then that was just before Christmas.
At that time, they had Skona before Christmas.

And so the next spring then, at senior banquet, I've forgotten who came to me, but whoever asked me could I. Oh, they had gone to Earl's office and found out that we were slated to go to Tarleton for the retirement of E.J.
Howe, who was president.
And they came and asked me if I could make some excuse and not go with Earl to Tarleton and bring Bob over there to the banquet because they were going to get this new puppy.
And so that's what I did.
And Bob was at the age where he
Didn't want to get out of his blue jeans or just bored him to death to dress up.
But I finally got him to go with me.
And they gave him the dog.
And when that dog was two years old, Earl was home.
I mean, Earl and was home visiting.
And Earl said, come on, let's go out.
Let me show you a lot at the lake, Carter Lake.
And Had Davis at that time had the two lots next to ours where Frank Vandiver lives now.
And so he had a little rowboat.
And he asked Bob if he wanted to take it out, and of course Bob did.
And when Bob got in the boat, the dog jumped in with him.
He rowed out kind of in the center of the lake, and without any warning, the dog just dived in.
Drowned.
Oh, my.
And, oh, it just upset Bob something awful.
But anyway, there, that one went.
And so we got that dog buried before they could have a big funeral.
In the days, the present days here, what did y'all do for relaxation?
Not much.
Movies were out of the ordinary.
I remember one night he said, I want us to go to the movie.
And they were showing Darby's Rangers.
It was a movie.
And I don't remember us going to any other movie together.
Did he go fishing, hunting?
He was not a hunter.
Now, if somebody wanted to go to the ranch and hunt, maybe he'd go with them, but he was not much of a hunter.
And he didn't fish much, did he?
No.
He just didn't have many...
And you all didn't take many long vacation trips.
In 1967, it was simply because he was to go to these places that A&M had something going.
But we did kind of, he took me along and made, you know, he paid for me.
And we did go around the world at that time because you get a certain distance away, you might as well go around the rest of the way.
So we did that.
We were gone close to a month.
That's the longest.
Do you remember any accomplishments that you think gave him great pride here?
Any changes?
Oh, at A&M?
I think the fact that he got
the changes made that he felt like it had to be made for A&M to grow.
I think that was something he was proud of.
Okay.
But he didn't live to see what really happened.
Right.
Do you remember any things that you think were frustrations to him that he wished he could have done?
Nope.
I can't think of anything offhand.
I don't have any in mind.
No, I can't think of any.
One day...
I was in his office and he asked me about Private Slovik.
Does that name ring a bell?
That little red book right there.
And he told me that that was just about one of the toughest things he'd ever had to be a part of.
That was a stupid movie, too.
Yeah, the movie was particular.
Then in my last conversation with him, you may have heard me say,
to others, I said to him, nobody but you could have done all that.
And he said, oh, why?

And I said, because nobody could have said you weren't a Texan, you weren't an Aggie, you hadn't served your country, that you're one of those fuddy-duddy PhDs that's just here for a little while passing through, and that you don't know Governor Conley and President Johnson.
And he leaned back and smiled and he said, oh, I never thought about any of that.
And I said, yeah, I'm sure you didn't.
He was funny.
He just, you know, Earl just, he didn't have a big ego.
No.
Now, let's see.
And he didn't play cards with a group of the buddies, did he?
He didn't shoot pool.
No, he just didn't.
He didn't relax a whole lot.
See that little red book right there on top?
It should be a mark in there of his message to his troops after the execution.
See, he didn't have anything to do with the decision.
Oh, I know.
It had already been made and approved all the way up to Eisenhower.
Right.
No, let's see.
There it is.
There it is.
No?
Did you find his message to his troops?
Yes, ma'am.
Read that.
It's pretty straightforward.
Oh, yes.

uh the uh now he did enjoy going to the ranch didn't he yeah just to go yeah drive around yeah uh not very long after he was home i remember my dad thought he'd probably lost his mind he bought a d8 tractor and he hired a operator to
Well, they would go and bulldoze all the way around all the pastures, you know.
And, oh, it did all kinds of things.
And Earl loved nothing better than get there on the thing and ride it.
He loved it.
But he wasn't...
He didn't really...

do too much ranching he always just had somebody hired to do that all right let's uh we'll go on the on the the finish up now when did his health begin to decline I didn't really I was not aware of it you know being around him every day but uh in let's see in 1969 he was invited
by British TV to be in a film called 10 Men Went to War.
And what it would do, they'd take these 10 men.
One of them was a fellow you talked about hanging on the steeple in St. Mary's Glace.
And Earl's, of course, was a Point to Hope thing.
And they would take them to where something significant had happened to them during the war.
And then they'd film them in their present location.
And Earl was real pleased to have them come here before the crew came here.
And he had them observe a final review and I don't know what all.
Oh, I do too know that they wanted to film his ranch activities, but it was too far to go to the ranch.
It's about a four and a half hour drive to go out there.
And I've got to go out there if the doctor will let me.
10th of July, we're going to have the family reunion.
It's my turn.
So we're going to do it, but we're not going to do it at the house.
We're going to do it in Menard at the little country club because there's a pool there and the little ones like to swim.
But I got wound up and distracted.
What was I talking about?
Oh, you were talking about his health and the crew.
Oh, his health.
But this film,
I didn't realize, but when I saw the film, and we got a copy of it after he was gone, he never saw it.
They filmed it, British TV did, for the 25th anniversary of D-Day, thinking they could get it shown over here too, but it didn't happen.
And I could tell by listening to his voice there that something was wrong.
So I don't really know when I noticed it sort of going, but...
When he came in the day that he got sick in the night, we had the doctor, which is OC, come.
And I thought maybe he got sick because I had the help doing something else and I fixed Mexican food.
I thought maybe that made him sick.
I don't know.
But we put him in the hospital the next morning.
And so...
I guess it was the next night that he had sort of a stroke, she thought.
And O.C.
said, I think we ought to take him to Houston.
And I had driven Earl.
See, he had me driving him, too, at the last thing.
And I had driven him down for a meeting of the Tentacle Executive Board.
That was a once-proud company that's gone down the drain.
Oh, it makes me ill. And I held on to it, wouldn't you know?
But Lupo's wife, Evelyn, was in the hospital at the medical center.
So after Earl got through this business stuff, we went out to see her.
And when we got there, Earl said, this is one of the finest medical complexes in the world.
So I thought, that's where we need to go then.
So the ambulance, of course, took him in OC, said he would ride the ambulance with him and for me not to try to think I could get there by the time they did.
Now that's March or January?
Oh, January.
He was there two months before he died.
As you look back yourself on these A&M years, which friends do you cherish the most?
Well, you know, it's kind of like my sister-in-law and Brady who died a year or so ago.
She said all of her friends were in the cemetery.
So the ones that I was with the most have passed on.
Oh, but what?
You know, the dean's wives.
We were sort of a close-knit group.
Others, were there, did you have any special friends off campus?
I don't know when Ann White and I got started.
She's my running buddy now.
Yeah, I think of Ann as a special friend.
Oh, she's a very special friend.
Now, let's see, y'all Methodist?
Yeah.
And like I've heard down through the years, some stories that it helped if you were a Methodist or a Presbyterian to be in the administration at...
at A&M.
We used to call it the Methodist Mafia.
Yeah, that's... Because, see, Gib Geltrude started with him, and then, I don't know, anybody between him and Earl.
And, of course, Jack Williams was Methodist.
Weren't the Harringtons Methodists?
No, they were Baptists.
Oh, that's right.
They were Baptists, yes.
Very Baptists.
Yes, yes, yes, yes, yes.
Yeah.
And the Williams certainly were... Methodists.
All right.
Were you aware of communication between Mr. Rutter and Jack Williams in 1969?
Well, when Jack came down here, I don't know what the exact title was, the head of kind of education.
Commissioner of Higher Education.
Yeah.
They came over here, and Earl said something to me about making Jack executive vice president.
This was long before Earl died.
Not real long, but last year or so.
And I think Earl, he never told me.
But I really think that he had planned to retire about the time he and him had their centennial, 76.
And he called me one day and just like he's kind of like my dad.
My dad would have a land deal figured out before he let my mother in on it.
He's going to buy this ranch.
But Earl sent.
Well.
Bill Carl, was that his name?
The real estate man?
He said, I'm going to send Bill to pick you up.
I want him to show you something.
That's all he told me.
And you know where the A&M setup is out near the Brazos River, where they're having so much trouble, the people across the road don't want the pigs?
Earl could have bought that whole thing for 500 an acre.
Oh, how beautiful.
And he wanted me to see the house that was there.

I guess he's still there I don't know but anyway he had Bill Carlton pick me up and take me out there and show me that house and I guess he would have gone ahead and bought it if I had been a little more in favor of it but I said I don't know what you want to do with any more land I said you don't have time to look after what we have and see what we did my parents gave us half of the ranch and then my dad
uh, called one day and said for us to come out and not bring the children.
I thought, what's the matter with him?
He never told us not to bring the children.
And it was because he wanted to talk business.
He said, it's not very often you can buy a piece of land that joins you.
Well, the same amount that we had been given, see, he gave the two brothers more than he gave my sister and me, but that was okay.
Anyway, he had deeded this to my younger brother that had the home place on it, their house and all.
And it did join what we had had.
And so we agreed to buy it before we came home that night.
And Earl made the last payment on that in December and got sick in January.
Just had paid it off.
And paid on it 20 years.
So at least that was paid off.
He would have gone in debt and left me with a debt of a million dollars, and I think it would have driven me crazy, because I don't like debt now.
My dad liked debt, but I didn't like debt.
But what he told me that day has turned out to be what's happened.
It had three miles of riverfront, and I said, I don't know what you want, more land?
He said, well, I figured that I could develop the half of it
closest to College Station and make enough off of that to clear the other half.
I said you probably could but when you're going to have time.
So he never did go through it but he was right about to.
And you know there's nice homes on that part that's close to College Station.
I've always thought to live on the east side of the river on the high bank looking across the river would be a very special place.
Well I do know this that
You know John Knox and his wife Lou, they bought some and it was 1,500 acres by the time they bought it so it was going up.
Earl could have bought it at 500 acres.
Let's see, can you think of any topics that we haven't touched on?
I think I just shoot the breeze and don't say much of anything.
No, no, no.
This is just special.
I want to close by thanking you and assure you that when we get this typed, we'll get it back to you for you to edit in whatever fashion you want.
Let's see.
Let's make believe that somebody gave you a million dollars now with the stipulation that you were to give it to Texas A&M for whatever reason.

cause you want what would you want them to do with the money well I don't really know but you know when I was on student government at that other school in Austin we passed a resolution requesting that the board establish a school of fine arts and they did and it's it's going great guns and I think A&M should have one well I understand that's part of vision 2020 dream yeah
Vision 2020 Dream.
Let me close then by thanking you and my deep appreciation, and I'll turn this machine off.
